{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"69a049cc-d28f-461d-ac96-4f601a38f97a","content":"Here's the program and its output:\n\n**Program.cs**\n```csharp\nusing System.Text.Json;\n\nvar person = new Person(\"Alice\", 30);\n\nvar options = new JsonSerializerOptions\n{\n    PropertyNamingPolicy = JsonNamingPolicy.PascalCase,\n    WriteIndented = true\n};\n\nstring json = JsonSerializer.Serialize(person, options);\nConsole.WriteLine(json);\n\npublic record Person(string name, int age);\n```\n\n**Output:**\n```json\n{\n  \"Name\": \"Alice\",\n  \"Age\": 30\n}\n```\n\n`JsonNamingPolicy.PascalCase` is new in .NET 11 — it joins the existing built-in policies (`CamelCase`, `SnakeCaseLower`, `SnakeCaseUpper`, `KebabCaseLower`, `KebabCaseUpper`). It converts your lowercase `name`/`age` properties to `Name`/`Age` automatically.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"84b8832f-eb6e-46e3-8d07-344c7d35abe3","outputTokens":239,"requestId":"F3C6:1AB7E8:1F6DBF5:22BE8C2:6A03CC03"},"id":"ff66f567-2739-45c7-83e0-74433bdeda86","timestamp":"2026-05-13T00:55:37.702Z","parentId":"6470fad4-05b6-44be-8f81-36370961a169"}
